transcription:  &quot;Este volume em que se trata por postillas os sinti[punctuation?] dos das epistolas, eluanges.(?) das Domingas, Ferias, e solemnidades da Igreja, he composto, e ajuntado por Guilhelme Parisiense, como se ve no prologo antecedente a'o principio das postillas, e n'as de quem dis o tittolo exterior.&quot;

(second line, fourth word: transcribed above as &quot;eluanges.&quot; may be &quot;e luanges.&quot; or &quot;el uanges.&quot; -- ?)

in spite of any inability to understand every single word -- this note specifies quite clearly that that this collection of postils (etc.? -- i'm unclear what else is specified) was written and collected by &quot;Guillermus, Parisiensis&quot; (established heading), as one can see in the preceding prologue and at the beginning(?) of the postils, and [importantly!] not as the title on the exterior [specifically, the spine] would indicate.

the spine has &quot;Ioannes Scotvs Sermones&quot;

wrong, wrong, wrong.  thanks to this note, we're all less misled.

i hazard the terrifically improbably guess:

&quot;Rihj&quot;

the potentially third letter has more of an &quot;h&quot; bend in vol. 1 of the 2 vol. set.

a lively description here:

&quot;... But on this occasion at least, unfaithful to the ruling passion of his life, he has been smitten, I should like to know why? by the old China-ware of Sevres, Dresden, and Japan. To the masterpieces of printing and binding, he now prefers enamels, earthenwares, crockeries, carpets, bronzes, all kinds of &quot; chiffonneries;&quot; and here is the ungrateful man, sending away from his house, too small now, these ... !  Farewell then to these selected books ... we cannot quite understand how it is possible to part before death with so fine a collection.&quot;

